## 1. Platform API Surfaces at a Glance

| Platform | Auth model | Base URL / Port | Rate limit | API status |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Notion** | Bearer token (`ntn_*`) or OAuth 2.0 | `api.notion.com/v1` | 3 req/s per integration | Stable; `Notion-Version: 2025-09-03` required |
| **Fourthwall** | HTTP Basic (username:password) or OAuth | `api.fourthwall.com/open-api/v1/` | 100 req / 10s rolling window | V1_BETA (open to all creators) |
| **YouTube Data API v3** | API key (public) or OAuth 2.0 | `googleapis.com/youtube/v3` | **10,000 units/day** per project | Stable; quota cost per endpoint |
| **Discord** | Bot token / OAuth2 / Webhook URL | `discord.com/api/v10` | 50 req/s global; 5/2s per webhook | Stable; v10 current |
| **OBS WebSocket v5** | SHA256 challenge-response password | `ws://127.0.0.1:4455` | No rate limit (local) | Bundled in OBS 28+; current OBS 32.0.4 |

### Notion

**Required header on every API call:** `Notion-Version: 2025-09-03`. The 2025-09-03 version introduced multi-source databases — if you are building new integrations now, build to the current model and this is a non-issue. It only matters when inheriting a legacy Zapier/n8n setup built against the old `databases` API.

Key endpoints: `POST /v1/pages` (create database entries), `PATCH /v1/pages/{id}` (update properties), `POST /v1/data_sources/{id}/query` (filter/sort queries), `GET /v1/blocks/{id}/children` (page body). Pagination tops at `page_size=100`, max 100 blocks per append, 3 req/s average with `Retry-After` on 429s.

Notion **cannot receive inbound webhooks** to create or update data natively. External data must enter via direct API calls or middleware. Notion can *send* outbound webhooks via database automations (the "Send webhook" action fires HTTP POST with page property data). Integration API webhooks deliver sparse payloads — entity ID + timestamp only — requiring follow-up calls for content.

### Fourthwall (V1_BETA — open to all creators)

Three distinct APIs: **Platform API** (orders, products, fulfillment, donations, mailing list, webhooks — Basic Auth), **Storefront API** (public-facing, read-only, uses `ptkn_*` tokens), **Memberships API** (membership posts and content). OpenAPI spec: `docs.fourthwall.com/open-api-docs/open-api.yaml`. Any creator with SUPER ADMIN role can generate credentials under Settings → For Developers → Open API.

**15 confirmed webhook event types:** `ORDER_PLACED`, `ORDER_UPDATED`, `GIFT_PURCHASE`, `DONATION`, `PRODUCT_CREATED`, `PRODUCT_UPDATED`, `COLLECTION_UPDATED`, `SUBSCRIPTION_PURCHASED`, `SUBSCRIPTION_CHANGED`, `SUBSCRIPTION_EXPIRED`, `THANK_YOU_SENT`, `NEWSLETTER_SUBSCRIBED`, `PLATFORM_APP_DISCONNECTED`, `GIFT_DRAW_STARTED`, `GIFT_DRAW_ENDED`.

Webhooks use **HMAC-SHA256 signing** via `X-Fourthwall-Hmac-SHA256` header. Client must respond **200 OK within 2000ms** or delivery fails with retries. Test events carry `"testMode": true`.

### YouTube Data API v3

**10,000 units/day** per Google Cloud project, resetting at midnight Pacific. `search.list` costs 100 units (biggest budget threat). `videos.list` and `liveBroadcasts.list` cost 1 unit each. Failed requests still consume quota. The Channel Memberships API (`members.list`, `membershipsLevels.list`) requires an explicit access grant from YouTube.

### Discord (API v10)

Three auth paths: **Bot tokens** for server-to-server, **OAuth2 bearer tokens** for user-delegated actions, **webhook URLs** (token embedded in URL, no header needed). Key endpoint: `PUT /guilds/{id}/members/{user_id}/roles/{role_id}` for role assignment (requires `MANAGE_ROLES`). Webhook execution: `POST /webhooks/{id}/{token}` supporting rich embeds, custom avatars, and thread targeting.

**2025 rate limit change:** All webhooks within a guild may now share the same rate limit bucket (5 requests per 2 seconds), regardless of target channel. At low volume this is unlikely to cause issues, but burst scenarios could trigger throttling. Mitigation: use a single webhook URL with middleware fan-in rather than multiple independent webhooks.

### OBS WebSocket v5

Bundled with OBS Studio since v28 (current: OBS 32.0.4). **v4 → v5 was a complete protocol rewrite** — all event/request names changed, port moved 4444 → 4455, added OpCode-based Hello/Identify/Identified handshake. v4 client libraries are incompatible with v5. Critical event for creator automation: **`StreamStateChanged`** fires with `outputActive` (bool) and `outputState` string. WebSocket server is **local-only** — external services cannot connect without tunneling.

