## 2. Low-Hanging Fruit: Integration Chains Ranked by Effort

All chains follow the same pattern: **something changes in Platform A → signal fires → Platform B updates, or Notion logs it.** The goal is to eliminate as many legs of that chain as possible.

### Tier 1 — Zero-code, native, deploy today

**Fourthwall → Discord membership roles (native integration)**
Fourthwall's built-in Discord perk handles the OAuth linking flow. Setup: Dashboard → Memberships → Perks → add "Discord" perk type → connect server → map Scrivener and Keeper tiers to Discord roles. The Fourthwall bot manages assignment and removal automatically. Role removal is automatic on subscription expiry. Limitation: membership-only — does not work for one-time product purchases.

**OBS → Discord stream alerts (StreamNotifier plugin)**
An OBS Python script that fires Discord webhook messages on stream start/stop with customizable embeds and up to 10 dynamic fields. Install: OBS Tools → Scripts → add StreamNotifier. Requires Python 3.11+ and `pip install discord_webhook`. No middleware, no cloud dependency, works offline. Runs inside OBS via `OBS_FRONTEND_EVENT_STREAMING_STARTED` callback.

**YouTube → Discord upload/live notifications (NotifyMe or Pingcord)**
Dedicated Discord bots that handle PubSubHubbub subscription management, lease renewal, and rich embed formatting. Free tier, web dashboard setup, typically seconds-to-minutes latency. NotifyMe supports YouTube, Twitch, TikTok, and Kick. Pingcord supports filters by video type (live, Shorts, uploads). No coding, no middleware cost.

### Tier 2 — One middleware step, minimal configuration

**Fourthwall webhooks → Discord order/donation notifications (fw-webhooks.vercel.app)**
Community-built proxy: input your Discord webhook URL and embed color, receive a forwarding URL to paste into Fourthwall's webhook settings. Zero middleware cost, instant forwarding, transforms Fourthwall JSON payload into a Discord embed. Best for simple order/donation notifications.

**Fourthwall → Notion order logging (Zapier)**
Zapier is the only major middleware platform with a native Fourthwall app. Use "New Order Placed" trigger (instant) → Notion "Create Database Item" action. Map `data.friendlyId` → Order ID, `data.email` → Email, `data.amounts.total.value` → Total, `data.username` → Supporter Name. Same pattern works for `SUBSCRIPTION_PURCHASED`, `DONATION`, and all 12 Fourthwall trigger types.

**Notion database property change → Discord announcement (Zapier or n8n)**
Notion's "Updated Database Item" trigger → Discord "Send Channel Message" action. Alternatively, Notion's native "Send webhook" automation action fires on property changes with a JSON payload — but Notion's outbound format doesn't match Discord's embed schema. Cleanest path: Notion automation → webhook → n8n/Make → reformat → Discord webhook.

### Tier 3 — Bridge script + middleware, moderate setup

**OBS StreamStateChanged → Notion stream logging**
No direct path. Two approaches:

- **Advanced Scene Switcher plugin + curl (no code):** Configure a macro in OBS's Advanced Scene Switcher to execute `curl.exe -X POST https://hook.make.com/URL?action=stream_started` on stream state changes. Make.com/n8n receives the webhook and creates a Notion entry.
- **obs-websocket-js bridge (~20 lines Node.js):** Connects to `ws://127.0.0.1:4455`, listens for `StreamStateChanged`, POSTs to a Make.com/n8n webhook URL with stream metadata.

**YouTube PubSubHubbub → middleware → Discord + Notion**
Subscribe to `https://pubsubhubbub.appspot.com/subscribe` with topic `https://www.youtube.com/xml/feeds/videos.xml?channel_id=YOUR_CHANNEL_ID` and callback pointing to an n8n/Pipedream webhook. On notification: parse Atom XML, call `videos.list?id=VIDEO_ID&part=snippet,liveStreamingDetails` (1 unit) to check `snippet.liveBroadcastContent == "live"`, then fan out to Discord webhook and Notion API. Lease expires every ~9.6 days — must re-subscribe proactively.

