## 3. Clever Solutions from the Community

**Fourthwall order → Discord role for non-members (custom bot `/verify` pattern)**
The native integration only handles membership tiers, not one-time product purchases. Proven pattern: build a Discord bot with a `/verify` slash command where customers enter their Fourthwall order email. Bot queries `GET /orders?email=...` to validate, then calls `PUT /guilds/{id}/members/{user_id}/roles/{role_id}` to assign a "Customer" role. This is the only reliable solution to identity linking for non-membership purchases.

**Notion Custom Agents as glue logic**
Custom Agents launched February 24, 2026 — autonomous AI agents that run on triggers (schedule, page created/updated, @mentions). Free through May 3, 2026, then credit-based at $10 per 1,000 credits. Best use: judgment-requiring tasks like monitoring a Stream Log database and auto-generating Discord recap summaries. Not best use: deterministic event routing (webhook → create row → post embed), where agents add latency and cost for no reasoning benefit.

**Streamer.bot as a universal bridge**
Fourthwall has a direct Streamer.bot integration receiving purchase, donation, and gifting events. Streamer.bot also integrates with OBS WebSocket v5 and can fire webhook actions. Creates an alternative path: Fourthwall → Streamer.bot → OBS scene changes + Discord webhooks + HTTP actions → Notion. Particularly useful for on-stream purchase alerts that simultaneously trigger OBS overlays and log to Notion.

**Node-RED for visual OBS automation**
The `node-red-contrib-obs-ws` package provides visual flow nodes for OBS WebSocket v5. Combined with Node-RED's built-in HTTP request nodes, this creates a drag-and-drop interface for OBS → external webhook bridges without writing code. Runs locally alongside OBS.

**Notion Markdown API for programmatic content writing**
⚠️ **Verification required before building against this.** The document that sourced this claims a Markdown API (`GET /v1/pages/{id}/markdown`, `PATCH /v1/pages/{id}/markdown`) was added February 26, 2026, with SDK methods in `@notionhq/client` v5.11.0+. This is specific enough to be real but was not captured in OIS research as of March 4, 2026. Verify against `developers.notion.com/page/changelog` before building any workflow that depends on it.

