## 5. Notion-Specific: Automations, Agents, and the Markdown API

**Native automation layer** supports three trigger types on databases: Page added, Property edited (with sub-conditions), and Every {frequency} (scheduled). Actions: edit property, add/edit pages in other databases, send notification, send email (Gmail), **send webhook** (HTTP POST, max 5 per automation), send Slack notification, define variables. Automations are database-scoped, cannot chain (automation output cannot trigger another automation), and require paid plans (Free plan gets Slack notifications only).

**The "Send webhook" action** is the key outbound mechanism from Notion. Fires HTTP POST with page property data in JSON — property values only, not page content/body. No authentication headers on the outgoing POST. Page buttons can also fire webhooks but only with static custom headers. This enables: Calendar milestone marked "Complete" → webhook → middleware → Discord announcement.

**Integration webhooks** (developer API, distinct from automation webhooks) push notifications when content changes. Events: `page.created`, `page.content_updated`, `page.property_values.updated`, `page.deleted`, `page.moved`, `comment.created`, `data_source.created`, `data_source.schema_updated`. Payloads are sparse — metadata only. Verification uses `X-Notion-Signature` (HMAC-SHA256). Retry: up to 8 times over ~24 hours.

**Markdown API** — ⚠️ Verify before building. Claimed to allow `GET /v1/pages/{id}/markdown` and `PATCH /v1/pages/{id}/markdown` for reading/writing page content as Enhanced Markdown rather than JSON block arrays. Check `developers.notion.com/page/changelog` to confirm availability before building any workflow that depends on this capability.

**Custom Agents (Notion 3.3, February 24, 2026)** — Free through May 3, 2026. Credit-based after: $10 per 1,000 credits (~30-60 simple runs per 1,000 credits). Available models include Claude Sonnet, Claude Opus 4.6, GPT-5, and Gemini 3 Pro. Best use: judgment-requiring glue logic (stream recap generation, content classification, cross-database synthesis). Not best use: deterministic event routing where a simple webhook → API call chain is more reliable and cheaper.

